<text>In mathematics, Stirling&#x27;s approximation (or Stirling&#x27;s formula) is an asymptotic approximation for factorials. It is a good approximation, leading to accurate results even for small values of formula_1. It is named after James Stirling, though a related but less precise result was first stated by Abraham de Moivre.

One way of stating the approximation involves the logarithm of the factorial:
formula_2
where the big O notation means that, for all sufficiently large values of formula_1, the difference between formula_4 and formula_5 will be at most proportional to the logarithm of formula_1. In computer science applications such as the worst-case lower bound for comparison sorting, it is convenient to instead use the binary logarithm, giving the equivalent form
formula_7 The error term in either base can be expressed more precisely as formula_8, corresponding to an approximate formula for the factorial itself,
formula_9
Here the sign formula_10 means that the two quantities are asymptotic, that is, their ratio tends to 1 as formula_1 tends to infinity.

